l2tp.description: The MIB module that describes managed objects of general use by the Layer Two Transport Protocol.

L2tpMilliSeconds.name: L2tpMilliSeconds
L2tpMilliSeconds.description: A period of time measured in units of .001 of seconds when used in conjunction with the DISPLAY-HINT will show seconds and fractions of second with a resolution of .001 of a second.

l2tpAdminState.name: l2tpAdminState
l2tpAdminState.description: This object defines the administrative state of the L2TP protocol. Setting this object to 'disabled' causes all tunnels to be immediately disconnected and no further tunnels to be either initiated or accepted. The value of this object must be maintained in non-volatile memory.

l2tpDrainTunnels.name: l2tpDrainTunnels
l2tpDrainTunnels.description: Setting this object to 'true' will prevent any new tunnels and/or sessions to be either initiated or accepted but does NOT disconnect any active tunnels/sessions. Setting this object to true(1) causes all domains and their respective tunnels to transition to the draining state. Note that when this occurs the 'xxxDraining' status objects of the domains and their tunnels should reflect that they are 'draining'. Setting this object has no affect on the domains or their tunnels 'xxxDrainTunnels' configuration objects. To cancel a drain this object should be set to false(2). The object l2tpDrainingTunnels reflects the current L2TP draining state. The value of this object must be maintained in non-volatile memory.

l2tpProtocolVersions.name: l2tpProtocolVersions
l2tpProtocolVersions.description: Vector of supported L2TP protocol version and revision numbers. Supported versions are identified via a two octet pairing where the first octet indicates the version and the second octet contains the revision.

l2tpVendorName.name: l2tpVendorName
l2tpVendorName.description: This object identifies the Vendor name of the L2TP protocol stack.

l2tpFirmwareRev.name: l2tpFirmwareRev
l2tpFirmwareRev.description: This object defines the firmware revision for the L2TP protocol stack.

l2tpDrainingTunnels.name: l2tpDrainingTunnels
l2tpDrainingTunnels.description: This object indicates if the local L2TP is draining off sessions from all tunnels.

l2tpDomainConfigTable.name: l2tpDomainConfigTable
l2tpDomainConfigTable.description: The L2TP Domain configuration table. This table contains objects that can be used to configure the operational characteristics of a tunnel domain. There is a 1-1 correspondence between conceptual rows of this table and conceptual rows of the l2tpDomainStatsTable.

l2tpDomainConfigEntry.name: l2tpDomainConfigEntry
l2tpDomainConfigEntry.description: An L2TP Domain configuration entry. An entry in this table may correspond to a single endpoint or a group of tunnel endpoints.

l2tpDomainConfigId.name: l2tpDomainConfigId
l2tpDomainConfigId.description: The identifier, usually in the form of a Domain Name (full or partial), describing a single tunnel endpoint or a domain of tunnel endpoints. This is typically used as a 'handle' to identify the tunnel configuration requirements for both incoming and outgoing tunnel connection attempts. Both the LAC and LNS could use information provided in the Host Name AVP attribute however the tunnel initiator could use other means not specified to identify the domain's tunnel configuration requirements. For example; three rows in this table have l2tpDomainConfigId values of 'lac1.isp.com', 'isp.com' and 'com'. A tunnel endpoint then identifies itself as 'lac1.isp.com' which would match the 'lac1.isp.com' entry in this table. A second tunnel endpoint then identifies itself as 'lac2.isp.com'. This endpoint is then associated with the 'isp.com' entry of this table.

l2tpDomainConfigAdminState.name: l2tpDomainConfigAdminState
l2tpDomainConfigAdminState.description: This object defines the administrative state of this tunnel domain. Setting this object to disabled(2) causes all tunnels to be immediately disconnected and no further tunnels to be either initiated or accepted. Note that all columnar objects corresponding to this conceptual row cannot be modified when the administrative state is enabled EXCEPT those objects which specifically state otherwise.

l2tpDomainConfigDrainTunnels.name: l2tpDomainConfigDrainTunnels
l2tpDomainConfigDrainTunnels.description: Setting this object to 'true' will prevent any new tunnels and/or sessions from being either initiated or accepted but does NOT disconnect any active tunnels/sessions for this tunnel domain. Setting this object to true(1) causes all tunnels within this domain to transition to the draining state. Note that when this occurs the l2tpTunnelStatsDrainingTunnel status objects of all of this domain's tunnels should reflect that they are 'draining'. Setting this object has no effect on this domain's associated tunnels l2tpTunnelConfigDrainTunnel configuration objects. To cancel a drain this object should be set to false(2). Setting this object to false(2) when the L2TP object l2tpDrainTunnels is true(1) has no affect, all domains and their tunnels will continue to drain.

l2tpDomainConfigAuth.name: l2tpDomainConfigAuth
l2tpDomainConfigAuth.description: This object describes how tunnel peers belonging to this domain are to be authenticated. The value simple(2) indicates that peers are authenticated simply by their host name as described in the Host Name AVP. The value challenge(3) indicates that all peers are challenged to prove their identification. This mechanism is described in the L2TP protocol.

l2tpDomainConfigSecret.name: l2tpDomainConfigSecret
l2tpDomainConfigSecret.description: This object is used to configure the shared secret used during the tunnel authentication phase of tunnel establishment. This object MUST be accessible only via requests using both authentication and privacy. The agent MUST report an empty string in response to get, get-next and get-bulk requests.

l2tpDomainConfigTunnelSecurity.name: l2tpDomainConfigTunnelSecurity
l2tpDomainConfigTunnelSecurity.description: This object defines whether this tunnel domain requires that all tunnels are to be secured. The value of ipsec(3) indicates that all tunnel packets, control and session, have IP Security headers. The type of IP Security headers (AH, ESP etc) and how they are further described is outside the scope of this document.

l2tpDomainConfigTunnelHelloInt.name: l2tpDomainConfigTunnelHelloInt
l2tpDomainConfigTunnelHelloInt.description: This object defines the interval in which Hello (or keep-alive) packets are to be sent by local peers belonging to this tunnel domain. The value zero effectively disables the sending of Hello packets. This object may be modified when the administrative state is enabled for this conceptual row.

l2tpDomainConfigTunnelIdleTO.name: l2tpDomainConfigTunnelIdleTO
l2tpDomainConfigTunnelIdleTO.description: This object defines the period of time that an established tunnel belonging to this tunnel domain with no active sessions will wait before disconnecting the tunnel. A value of zero indicates that the tunnel will disconnect immediately after the last session disconnects. A value of -1 leaves the tunnel up indefinitely. This object may be modified when the administrative state is enabled for this conceptual row.

l2tpDomainConfigControlRWS.name: l2tpDomainConfigControlRWS
l2tpDomainConfigControlRWS.description: This object defines the control channel receive window size for tunnels belonging to this domain. It specifies the maximum number of packets the tunnel peer belonging to this domain can send without waiting for an acknowledgement from this peer.

l2tpDomainConfigControlMaxRetx.name: l2tpDomainConfigControlMaxRetx
l2tpDomainConfigControlMaxRetx.description: This object defines the maximum number of retransmissions which the L2TP stack will attempt for tunnels belonging to this domain before assuming that the peer is no longer responding.

l2tpDomainConfigControlMaxRetxTO.name: l2tpDomainConfigControlMaxRetxTO
l2tpDomainConfigControlMaxRetxTO.description: This object defines the maximum retransmission timeout interval which the L2TP stack will wait for tunnels belonging to this domain before retransmitting a control packet that has not been acknowledged.

l2tpDomainConfigPayloadSeq.name: l2tpDomainConfigPayloadSeq
l2tpDomainConfigPayloadSeq.description: This object determines whether or not session payload packets will be requested to be sent with sequence numbers from tunnel peers belonging to this domain. The value onDemand(1) allows the L2TP implementation to initiate payload sequencing when necessary based on local information (e.g: during LCP/NCP negotiations or for CCP). The value never(2) indicates that L2TP will never initiate sequencing but will do sequencing if asked. The value always(3) indicates that L2TP will send the Sequencing Required AVP during session establishment.

l2tpDomainConfigReassemblyTO.name: l2tpDomainConfigReassemblyTO
l2tpDomainConfigReassemblyTO.description: This object defines the number of milliseconds that local peers of this tunnel domain will wait before processing payload packets that were received out of sequence (which are waiting for the packet(s) to put them in sequence). A low value increases the chance of delayed packets to be discarded (which MAY cause the PPP decompression engine to reset) while a high value may cause more queuing and possibly degrade throughput if packets are truly lost. The default value for this object is zero which will result in all delayed packets being lost.

l2tpDomainConfigProxyPPPAuth.name: l2tpDomainConfigProxyPPPAuth
l2tpDomainConfigProxyPPPAuth.description: This object is used to configure the sending or acceptance of the PPP Proxy Authentication AVP's on the LAC or LNS.

l2tpDomainConfigStorageType.name: l2tpDomainConfigStorageType
l2tpDomainConfigStorageType.description: The storage type for this conceptual row. Conceptual rows having the value 'permanent' must allow write-access at a minimum to: - l2tpDomainConfigAdminState and l2tpDomainConfigDrainTunnels at all times - l2tpDomainConfigSecret if l2tpDomainConfigAuth has been configured as 'challenge' It is an implementation issue to decide if a SET for a readOnly or permanent row is accepted at all. In some contexts this may make sense, in others it may not. If a SET for a readOnly or permanent row is not accepted at all, then a 'wrongValue' error must be returned.

l2tpDomainConfigStatus.name: l2tpDomainConfigStatus
l2tpDomainConfigStatus.description: The status of this Domain entry. Columnar objects corresponding to this conceptual row may be modified according to their description clauses when this RowStatus object is 'active'.

l2tpDomainStatsTable.name: l2tpDomainStatsTable
l2tpDomainStatsTable.description: The L2TP Domain Status and Statistics table. This table contains objects that can be used to describe the current status and statistics of a tunnel domain. There is a 1-1 correspondence between conceptual rows of this table and conceptual rows of the l2tpDomainConfigTable.

l2tpDomainStatsEntry.name: l2tpDomainStatsEntry
l2tpDomainStatsEntry.description: An L2TP Domain Stats entry. An entry in this table may correspond to a single endpoint or a group of tunnel endpoints.

l2tpDomainStatsTotalTunnels.name: l2tpDomainStatsTotalTunnels
l2tpDomainStatsTotalTunnels.description: This object returns the total number of tunnels that have successfully reached the established state for this tunnel domain.

l2tpDomainStatsFailedTunnels.name: l2tpDomainStatsFailedTunnels
l2tpDomainStatsFailedTunnels.description: This object returns the number of tunnels that failed (eg: connection timeout, unsupported or malformed AVP's etc) to reach the established state for this tunnel domain.

l2tpDomainStatsFailedAuths.name: l2tpDomainStatsFailedAuths
l2tpDomainStatsFailedAuths.description: This object returns the number of failed tunnel connection attempts for this domain because the tunnel peer failed authentication.

l2tpDomainStatsActiveTunnels.name: l2tpDomainStatsActiveTunnels
l2tpDomainStatsActiveTunnels.description: This object returns the number of tunnels that are currently active for this domain.

l2tpDomainStatsTotalSessions.name: l2tpDomainStatsTotalSessions
l2tpDomainStatsTotalSessions.description: This object returns the total number of sessions that have successfully reached the established state for this tunnel domain.

l2tpDomainStatsFailedSessions.name: l2tpDomainStatsFailedSessions
l2tpDomainStatsFailedSessions.description: This object returns the number of sessions that failed (eg: connection timeout, unsupported or malformed AVP's etc) to reach the established state for this tunnel domain.

l2tpDomainStatsActiveSessions.name: l2tpDomainStatsActiveSessions
l2tpDomainStatsActiveSessions.description: This object returns the number of sessions that are currently active for this domain.

l2tpDomainStatsDrainingTunnels.name: l2tpDomainStatsDrainingTunnels
l2tpDomainStatsDrainingTunnels.description: This object indicates if this domain is draining off sessions from all tunnels.

l2tpDomainStatsControlRxOctets.name: l2tpDomainStatsControlRxOctets
l2tpDomainStatsControlRxOctets.description: This object returns the number of control channel octets received for this tunnel domain.

l2tpDomainStatsControlRxPkts.name: l2tpDomainStatsControlRxPkts
l2tpDomainStatsControlRxPkts.description: This object returns the number of control packets received for this tunnel domain.

l2tpDomainStatsControlTxOctets.name: l2tpDomainStatsControlTxOctets
l2tpDomainStatsControlTxOctets.description: This object returns the number of control channel octets that were transmitted to tunnel endpoints for this domain.

l2tpDomainStatsControlTxPkts.name: l2tpDomainStatsControlTxPkts
l2tpDomainStatsControlTxPkts.description: This object returns the number of control packets that were transmitted to tunnel endpoints for this domain.

l2tpDomainStatsPayloadRxOctets.name: l2tpDomainStatsPayloadRxOctets
l2tpDomainStatsPayloadRxOctets.description: This object returns the number of payload channel octets that were received for this tunnel domain.

l2tpDomainStatsPayloadRxPkts.name: l2tpDomainStatsPayloadRxPkts
l2tpDomainStatsPayloadRxPkts.description: This object returns the number of payload packets that were received for this tunnel domain.

l2tpDomainStatsPayloadRxDiscs.name: l2tpDomainStatsPayloadRxDiscs
l2tpDomainStatsPayloadRxDiscs.description: This object returns the number of received payload packets that were discarded by this tunnel domain.

l2tpDomainStatsPayloadTxOctets.name: l2tpDomainStatsPayloadTxOctets
l2tpDomainStatsPayloadTxOctets.description: This object returns the number of payload channel octets that were transmitted to tunnel peers within this tunnel domain.

l2tpDomainStatsPayloadTxPkts.name: l2tpDomainStatsPayloadTxPkts
l2tpDomainStatsPayloadTxPkts.description: This object returns the number of payload packets that were transmitted to tunnel peers within this tunnel domain.

l2tpDomainStatsControlHCRxOctets.name: l2tpDomainStatsControlHCRxOctets
l2tpDomainStatsControlHCRxOctets.description: This object is a 64-bit version of l2tpDomainStatsControlRxOctets.

l2tpDomainStatsControlHCRxPkts.name: l2tpDomainStatsControlHCRxPkts
l2tpDomainStatsControlHCRxPkts.description: This object is a 64-bit version of l2tpDomainStatsControlRxPkts.

l2tpDomainStatsControlHCTxOctets.name: l2tpDomainStatsControlHCTxOctets
l2tpDomainStatsControlHCTxOctets.description: This object is a 64-bit version of l2tpDomainStatsControlTxOctets.

l2tpDomainStatsControlHCTxPkts.name: l2tpDomainStatsControlHCTxPkts
l2tpDomainStatsControlHCTxPkts.description: This object is a 64-bit version of l2tpDomainStatsControlTxPkts.

l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCRxOctets.name: l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCRxOctets
l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCRxOctets.description: This object is a 64-bit version of l2tpDomainStatsPayloadRxOctets.

l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCRxPkts.name: l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCRxPkts
l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCRxPkts.description: This object is a 64-bit version of l2tpDomainStatsPayloadRxPkts.

l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCRxDiscs.name: l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCRxDiscs
l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCRxDiscs.description: This object is a 64-bit version of l2tpDomainStatsPayloadRxDiscs.

l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCTxOctets.name: l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCTxOctets
l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCTxOctets.description: This object is a 64-bit version of l2tpDomainStatsPayloadTxOctets.

l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCTxPkts.name: l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCTxPkts
l2tpDomainStatsPayloadHCTxPkts.description: This object is a 64-bit version of l2tpDomainStatsPayloadTxPkts.

l2tpTunnelConfigTable.name: l2tpTunnelConfigTable
l2tpTunnelConfigTable.description: The L2TP tunnel configuration table. This table contains objects that can be used to (re)configure the operational characteristics of a single L2TP tunnel. There is a 1-1 correspondence between conceptual rows of this table and conceptual rows of the l2tpTunnelStatsTable. Entries in this table have the same persistency characteristics as that of the tunnelConfigTable.

l2tpTunnelConfigEntry.name: l2tpTunnelConfigEntry
l2tpTunnelConfigEntry.description: A L2TP tunnel interface configuration entry. Entries in this table come and go as a result of protocol interactions or on management operations. The latter occurs when a row is instantiated in the tunnelConfigTable row and the encapsulation method is 'l2tp'.

l2tpTunnelConfigIfIndex.name: l2tpTunnelConfigIfIndex
l2tpTunnelConfigIfIndex.description: This value for this object is equal to the value of ifIndex of the Interfaces MIB for tunnel interfaces of type L2TP.

l2tpTunnelConfigDomainId.name: l2tpTunnelConfigDomainId
l2tpTunnelConfigDomainId.description: The tunnel domain that this tunnel belongs to. A LNS tunnel endpoint will typically inherit this value from the endpoint domain table. A LAC may be provided with this information during tunnel setup. When a zero length string is returned this tunnel does not belong belong to any particular domain.

l2tpTunnelConfigAuth.name: l2tpTunnelConfigAuth
l2tpTunnelConfigAuth.description: This object describes how L2TP tunnel peers are to be authenticated. The value 'simple' indicates that peers are authenticated simply by their host name as described in the Host Name AVP. The value 'challenge' indicates that all peers are challenged to prove their identification. This mechanism is described in the L2TP protocol. This object cannot be modified when the tunnel is in a connecting or connected state.

l2tpTunnelConfigSecret.name: l2tpTunnelConfigSecret
l2tpTunnelConfigSecret.description: This object is used to configure the shared secret used during the tunnel authentication phase of tunnel establishment. This object cannot be modified when the tunnel is in a connecting or connected state. This object MUST be accessible only via requests using both authentication and privacy. The agent MUST report an empty string in response to get, get-next and get-bulk requests.

l2tpTunnelConfigSecurity.name: l2tpTunnelConfigSecurity
l2tpTunnelConfigSecurity.description: This object defines whether this tunnel is to be secured. The value of 'ipSec' indicates that all tunnel packets, control and session, have IP Security headers. The type of IP Security headers (AH, ESP etc) and how they are further described is outside the scope of this document. This object cannot be modified when the tunnel is in a connecting or connected state.

l2tpTunnelConfigHelloInterval.name: l2tpTunnelConfigHelloInterval
l2tpTunnelConfigHelloInterval.description: This object defines the interval in which Hello (or keep-alive) packets are to be sent to the tunnel peer. The value zero effectively disables the sending of Hello packets. Modifications to this object have immediate effect.

l2tpTunnelConfigIdleTimeout.name: l2tpTunnelConfigIdleTimeout
l2tpTunnelConfigIdleTimeout.description: This object defines the period of time that an established tunnel with no sessions will wait before disconnecting the tunnel. A value of zero indicates that the tunnel will disconnect immediately after the last session disconnects. A value of -1 leaves the tunnel up indefinitely. Modifications to this object have immediate effect.

l2tpTunnelConfigControlRWS.name: l2tpTunnelConfigControlRWS
l2tpTunnelConfigControlRWS.description: This object defines the control channel receive window size. It specifies the maximum number of packets the tunnel peer can send without waiting for an acknowledgement from this peer. This object cannot be modified when the tunnel is in a con- necting or connected state.

l2tpTunnelConfigControlMaxRetx.name: l2tpTunnelConfigControlMaxRetx
l2tpTunnelConfigControlMaxRetx.description: This object defines the number of retransmissions which the tunnel will attempt before assuming that the peer is no longer responding. A value of zero indicates that this peer will not attempt to retransmit an unacknowledged control packet. Modifications to this object have immediate effect.

l2tpTunnelConfigControlMaxRetxTO.name: l2tpTunnelConfigControlMaxRetxTO
l2tpTunnelConfigControlMaxRetxTO.description: This object defines the maximum retransmission timeout interval which the tunnel will wait before retrans- mitting a control packet that has not been acknowledged. Modifications to this object have immediate effect.

l2tpTunnelConfigPayloadSeq.name: l2tpTunnelConfigPayloadSeq
l2tpTunnelConfigPayloadSeq.description: This object determines whether or not session payload packets will be requested to be sent with sequence numbers from tunnel peers belonging to this domain. The value onDemand(1) allows the L2TP implementation to initiate payload sequencing when necessary based on local information (e.g: during LCP/NCP negotiations or for CCP). The value never(2) indicates that L2TP will never initiate sequencing but will do sequencing if asked. The value always(3) indicates that L2TP will send the Sequencing Required AVP during session establishment. Modifications to this object have immediate effect.

l2tpTunnelConfigReassemblyTO.name: l2tpTunnelConfigReassemblyTO
l2tpTunnelConfigReassemblyTO.description: This object defines the number of milliseconds that this tunnel will wait before processing payload packets that were received out of sequence (which are waiting for the packet(s) to put them in sequence). A low value increases the chance of delayed packets to be discarded (which MAY cause the PPP decompression engine to reset) while a high value may cause more queuing and possibly degrade throughput if packets are truly lost. The default value for this object is zero which will result in all delayed packets being lost. Modifications to this object have immediate effect.

l2tpTunnelConfigTransport.name: l2tpTunnelConfigTransport
l2tpTunnelConfigTransport.description: This object defines the underlying transport media that is in use for this tunnel entry. Different tunnel transports may define MIB extensions to the L2TP tunnel table to realize the transport layer. For example if the value of this object is 'udpIp' then the value of ifIndex for this table may be used to determine state from the l2tpUdpStatsTable. This object cannot be modified when the tunnel is in a connecting or connected state.

l2tpTunnelConfigDrainTunnel.name: l2tpTunnelConfigDrainTunnel
l2tpTunnelConfigDrainTunnel.description: Setting this object to 'true' will prevent any new session from being either initiated or accepted but does NOT disconnect any active sessions for this tunnel. Note that when this occurs the l2tpTunnelStatsDrainingTunnel status object of this tunnel should reflect that it is 'draining'. To cancel a drain this object should be set to false(2). Setting this object to false(2) when the L2TP objects l2tpDrainTunnels or l2tpDomainConfigDrainTunnels is true(1) has no affect, this tunnels will continue to drain.

l2tpTunnelConfigProxyPPPAuth.name: l2tpTunnelConfigProxyPPPAuth
l2tpTunnelConfigProxyPPPAuth.description: This object is used to configure the sending or acceptance of the session PPP Proxy Authentication AVP's on the LAC or LNS.

l2tpTunnelStatsTable.name: l2tpTunnelStatsTable
l2tpTunnelStatsTable.description: The L2TP tunnel status and statistics table. This table contains objects that can be used to describe the current status and statistics of a single L2TP tunnel. There is a 1-1 correspondence between conceptual rows of this table and conceptual rows of the l2tpTunnelConfigTable.

l2tpTunnelStatsEntry.name: l2tpTunnelStatsEntry
l2tpTunnelStatsEntry.description: An L2TP tunnel interface stats entry.

l2tpTunnelStatsLocalTID.name: l2tpTunnelStatsLocalTID
l2tpTunnelStatsLocalTID.description: This object contains the local tunnel Identifier.

l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteTID.name: l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteTID
l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteTID.description: This object contains the remote tunnel Identifier.

l2tpTunnelStatsState.name: l2tpTunnelStatsState
l2tpTunnelStatsState.description: This field contains the current state of the control tunnel.

l2tpTunnelStatsInitiated.name: l2tpTunnelStatsInitiated
l2tpTunnelStatsInitiated.description: This object indicates whether the tunnel was initiated locally or by the remote tunnel peer.

l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteHostName.name: l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteHostName
l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteHostName.description: This object contains the host name as discovered during the tunnel establishment phase (via the Host Name AVP) of the L2TP peer. If the tunnel is idle this object should maintain its value from the last time it was connected.

l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteVendorName.name: l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteVendorName
l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteVendorName.description: This object identifies the vendor name of the peer's L2TP implementation. If the tunnel is idle this object should maintain its value from the last time it was connected.

l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteFirmwareRev.name: l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteFirmwareRev
l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteFirmwareRev.description: This object contains the tunnel peer's firmware revision number. If the tunnel is idle this object should maintain its value from the last time it was connected.

l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteProtocolVer.name: l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteProtocolVer
l2tpTunnelStatsRemoteProtocolVer.description: This object describes the protocol version and revision of the tunnel peers implementation. The first octet contains the protocol version. The second octet contains the protocol revision.

l2tpTunnelStatsInitialRemoteRWS.name: l2tpTunnelStatsInitialRemoteRWS
l2tpTunnelStatsInitialRemoteRWS.description: This object contains the initial remote peer's receive window size as indicated by the tunnel peer (in the RWS AVP) during the tunnel establishment phase. If the tunnel is idle this object should maintain its value from the last time it was connected.

l2tpTunnelStatsBearerCaps.name: l2tpTunnelStatsBearerCaps
l2tpTunnelStatsBearerCaps.description: This object describes the Bearer Capabilities of the tunnel peer. If the tunnel is idle this object should maintain its value from the last time it was connected.

l2tpTunnelStatsFramingCaps.name: l2tpTunnelStatsFramingCaps
l2tpTunnelStatsFramingCaps.description: This object describes the Framing Capabilities of the tunnel peer. If the tunnel is idle this object should maintain its value from the last time it was connected.

l2tpTunnelStatsControlRxPkts.name: l2tpTunnelStatsControlRxPkts
l2tpTunnelStatsControlRxPkts.description: This object contains the number of control packets received on the tunnel.

l2tpTunnelStatsControlRxZLB.name: l2tpTunnelStatsControlRxZLB
l2tpTunnelStatsControlRxZLB.description: This object returns a count of the number of Zero Length Body control packet acknowledgement packets that were received.

l2tpTunnelStatsControlOutOfSeq.name: l2tpTunnelStatsControlOutOfSeq
l2tpTunnelStatsControlOutOfSeq.description: This object returns a count of the number of control packets that were not received in the correct order (as per the sequence number) on this tunnel including out of window packets.

l2tpTunnelStatsControlOutOfWin.name: l2tpTunnelStatsControlOutOfWin
l2tpTunnelStatsControlOutOfWin.description: This object contains the number of control packets that were received outside of the offered receive window. It is implementation specific as to whether these packets are queued or discarded.

l2tpTunnelStatsControlTxPkts.name: l2tpTunnelStatsControlTxPkts
l2tpTunnelStatsControlTxPkts.description: This object contains the number of control packets that were transmitted to the tunnel peer.

l2tpTunnelStatsControlTxZLB.name: l2tpTunnelStatsControlTxZLB
l2tpTunnelStatsControlTxZLB.description: This object contains the number of Zero Length Body control packets transmitted to the tunnel peer.

l2tpTunnelStatsControlAckTO.name: l2tpTunnelStatsControlAckTO
l2tpTunnelStatsControlAckTO.description: This object returns a count of the number of control packet timeouts due to the lack of a timely acknowledgement from the tunnel peer.

l2tpTunnelStatsCurrentRemoteRWS.name: l2tpTunnelStatsCurrentRemoteRWS
l2tpTunnelStatsCurrentRemoteRWS.description: This object contains the current remote receive window size as determined by the local flow control mechanism employed.

l2tpTunnelStatsTxSeq.name: l2tpTunnelStatsTxSeq
l2tpTunnelStatsTxSeq.description: This object contains the next send sequence number for the control channel.

l2tpTunnelStatsTxSeqAck.name: l2tpTunnelStatsTxSeqAck
l2tpTunnelStatsTxSeqAck.description: This object contains the send sequence number that the tunnel peer has acknowledged for the control channel. The flow control state can be determined by subtracting the l2tpTunnelStatsTxSeq from l2tpTunnelStatsTxSeqAck and comparing this value to l2tpTunnelStatsCurrentRemoteRWS (taking into consideration sequence number wraps).

l2tpTunnelStatsRxSeq.name: l2tpTunnelStatsRxSeq
l2tpTunnelStatsRxSeq.description: This object contains the next receive sequence number expected to be received on this control channel.

l2tpTunnelStatsRxSeqAck.name: l2tpTunnelStatsRxSeqAck
l2tpTunnelStatsRxSeqAck.description: This object contains the last receive sequence number that was acknowledged back to the tunnel peer for the control channel.

l2tpTunnelStatsTotalSessions.name: l2tpTunnelStatsTotalSessions
l2tpTunnelStatsTotalSessions.description: This object contains the total number of sessions that this tunnel has successfully connected through to its tunnel peer since this tunnel was created.

l2tpTunnelStatsFailedSessions.name: l2tpTunnelStatsFailedSessions
l2tpTunnelStatsFailedSessions.description: This object contains the total number of sessions that were initiated but failed to reach the established phase.

l2tpTunnelStatsActiveSessions.name: l2tpTunnelStatsActiveSessions
l2tpTunnelStatsActiveSessions.description: This object contains the total number of sessions in the established state for this tunnel.

l2tpTunnelStatsLastResultCode.name: l2tpTunnelStatsLastResultCode
l2tpTunnelStatsLastResultCode.description: This object contains the last value of the result code as described in the Result Code AVP which caused the tunnel to disconnect.

l2tpTunnelStatsLastErrorCode.name: l2tpTunnelStatsLastErrorCode
l2tpTunnelStatsLastErrorCode.description: This object contains the last value of the error code as described in the Result Code AVP which caused the tunnel to disconnect.

l2tpTunnelStatsLastErrorMessage.name: l2tpTunnelStatsLastErrorMessage
l2tpTunnelStatsLastErrorMessage.description: This object contains the last value of the optional message as described in the Result Code AVP which caused the tunnel to disconnect.

l2tpTunnelStatsDrainingTunnel.name: l2tpTunnelStatsDrainingTunnel
l2tpTunnelStatsDrainingTunnel.description: This object indicates if this tunnel is draining off sessions. This object will return false(2) when the tunnel is not draining sessions or after the last session has disconnected when the tunnel is in the draining state.

l2tpSessionStatsTable.name: l2tpSessionStatsTable
l2tpSessionStatsTable.description: The L2TP session status and statistics table. This table contains the objects that can be used to describe the current status and statistics of a single L2TP tunneled session.

l2tpSessionStatsEntry.name: l2tpSessionStatsEntry
l2tpSessionStatsEntry.description: An L2TP session interface stats entry.

l2tpSessionStatsTunnelIfIndex.name: l2tpSessionStatsTunnelIfIndex
l2tpSessionStatsTunnelIfIndex.description: This object identifies the session's associated L2TP tunnel ifIndex value.

l2tpSessionStatsIfIndex.name: l2tpSessionStatsIfIndex
l2tpSessionStatsIfIndex.description: This object identifies the ifIndex value of the interface from which PPP packets are being tunneled. For example this could be a DS0 ifIndex on a LAC or it would be the PPP ifIndex on the LNS.

l2tpSessionStatsLocalSID.name: l2tpSessionStatsLocalSID
l2tpSessionStatsLocalSID.description: This object contains the local assigned session identifier for this session.

l2tpSessionStatsRemoteSID.name: l2tpSessionStatsRemoteSID
l2tpSessionStatsRemoteSID.description: This object contains the remote assigned session identifier for this session. When a session is starting this value may be zero until the remote tunnel endpoint has responded.

l2tpSessionStatsUserName.name: l2tpSessionStatsUserName
l2tpSessionStatsUserName.description: This object identifies the peer session name on this interface. This is typically the login name of the remote user. If the user name is unknown to the local tunnel peer then this object will contain a null string.

l2tpSessionStatsState.name: l2tpSessionStatsState
l2tpSessionStatsState.description: This object contains the current state of the session.

l2tpSessionStatsCallType.name: l2tpSessionStatsCallType
l2tpSessionStatsCallType.description: This object indicates the type of call and the role this tunnel peer is providing for this session. For example, lacIncoming(1) indicates that this tunnel peer is acting as a LAC and generated a Incoming-Call-Request to the tunnel peer (the LNS). Note that tunnel peers can be both LAC and LNS simultaneously.

l2tpSessionStatsCallSerialNumber.name: l2tpSessionStatsCallSerialNumber
l2tpSessionStatsCallSerialNumber.description: This object contains the serial number that has been assigned to this session.

l2tpSessionStatsTxConnectSpeed.name: l2tpSessionStatsTxConnectSpeed
l2tpSessionStatsTxConnectSpeed.description: This object returns the last known transmit baud rate for this session.

l2tpSessionStatsRxConnectSpeed.name: l2tpSessionStatsRxConnectSpeed
l2tpSessionStatsRxConnectSpeed.description: This object returns the last known receive baud rate for this session established.

l2tpSessionStatsCallBearerType.name: l2tpSessionStatsCallBearerType
l2tpSessionStatsCallBearerType.description: This object describes the bearer type of this session.

l2tpSessionStatsFramingType.name: l2tpSessionStatsFramingType
l2tpSessionStatsFramingType.description: This object describes the framing type of this session.

l2tpSessionStatsPhysChanId.name: l2tpSessionStatsPhysChanId
l2tpSessionStatsPhysChanId.description: This object contains the physical channel identifier for the session.

l2tpSessionStatsDNIS.name: l2tpSessionStatsDNIS
l2tpSessionStatsDNIS.description: This object identifies the Dialed Number Information String that the LAC obtained from the network for the session. If no DNIS was provided then a null string will be returned.

l2tpSessionStatsCLID.name: l2tpSessionStatsCLID
l2tpSessionStatsCLID.description: This object identifies the Calling Line ID that the LAC obtained from the network for the session. If no CLID was provided then a null string will be returned.

l2tpSessionStatsSubAddress.name: l2tpSessionStatsSubAddress
l2tpSessionStatsSubAddress.description: This object identifies the Sub Address that the LAC obtained from the network for the session. If no Sub Address was provided then a null string will be returned.

l2tpSessionStatsPrivateGroupID.name: l2tpSessionStatsPrivateGroupID
l2tpSessionStatsPrivateGroupID.description: This object identifies the Private Group Identifier used for this tunneled session. If no Private Group Identifier was provided then a null string will be returned.

l2tpSessionStatsProxyLcp.name: l2tpSessionStatsProxyLcp
l2tpSessionStatsProxyLcp.description: Indicates whether the LAC performed proxy LCP for this session.

l2tpSessionStatsAuthMethod.name: l2tpSessionStatsAuthMethod
l2tpSessionStatsAuthMethod.description: This object contains the proxy authentication method employed by the LAC for the session. If l2tpSessionProxyLcp is false(2) this object should not be interpreted.

l2tpSessionStatsSequencingState.name: l2tpSessionStatsSequencingState
l2tpSessionStatsSequencingState.description: This object defines which tunnel peers have requested payload sequencing. The value of both(4) indicates that both peers have requested payload sequencing.

l2tpSessionStatsOutSequence.name: l2tpSessionStatsOutSequence
l2tpSessionStatsOutSequence.description: This object returns the total number of packets received for this session which were received out of sequence.

l2tpSessionStatsReassemblyTO.name: l2tpSessionStatsReassemblyTO
l2tpSessionStatsReassemblyTO.description: This object returns the number of reassembly timeouts that have occurred for this session.

l2tpSessionStatsTxSeq.name: l2tpSessionStatsTxSeq
l2tpSessionStatsTxSeq.description: This object contains the next send sequence number for for this session.

l2tpSessionStatsRxSeq.name: l2tpSessionStatsRxSeq
l2tpSessionStatsRxSeq.description: This object contains the next receive sequence number expected to be received on this session.

l2tpTunnelMapTable.name: l2tpTunnelMapTable
l2tpTunnelMapTable.description: The L2TP Tunnel index mapping table. This table is intended to assist management applications to quickly determine what the ifIndex value is for a given local tunnel identifier.

l2tpTunnelMapEntry.name: l2tpTunnelMapEntry
l2tpTunnelMapEntry.description: An L2TP tunnel index map entry.

l2tpTunnelMapLocalTID.name: l2tpTunnelMapLocalTID
l2tpTunnelMapLocalTID.description: This object contains the local tunnel Identifier.

l2tpTunnelMapIfIndex.name: l2tpTunnelMapIfIndex
l2tpTunnelMapIfIndex.description: This value for this object is equal to the value of ifIndex of the Interfaces MIB for tunnel interfaces of type L2TP.

l2tpSessionMapTable.name: l2tpSessionMapTable
l2tpSessionMapTable.description: The L2TP Session index mapping table. This table is intended to assist management applications to map interfaces to a tunnel and session identifier.

l2tpSessionMapEntry.name: l2tpSessionMapEntry
l2tpSessionMapEntry.description: An L2TP Session index map entry.

l2tpSessionMapIfIndex.name: l2tpSessionMapIfIndex
l2tpSessionMapIfIndex.description: This object identifies the ifIndex value of the interface which is receiving or sending its packets over an L2TP tunnel. For example this could be a DS0 ifIndex on a LAC or a PPP ifIndex on the LNS.

l2tpSessionMapTunnelIfIndex.name: l2tpSessionMapTunnelIfIndex
l2tpSessionMapTunnelIfIndex.description: This object identifies the sessions associated L2TP tunnel ifIndex value. When this object is set it provides a binding between a particular interface identified by l2tpSessionMapIfIndex to a particular tunnel.

l2tpSessionMapLocalSID.name: l2tpSessionMapLocalSID
l2tpSessionMapLocalSID.description: This object contains the local assigned session identifier for this session.

l2tpSessionMapStatus.name: l2tpSessionMapStatus
l2tpSessionMapStatus.description: The status of this session map entry.

l2tpUdpStatsTable.name: l2tpUdpStatsTable
l2tpUdpStatsTable.description: The L2TP UDP/IP transport stats table. This table contains objects that can be used to describe the current status and statistics of the UDP/IP L2TP tunnel transport.

l2tpUdpStatsEntry.name: l2tpUdpStatsEntry
l2tpUdpStatsEntry.description: An L2TP UDP/IP transport stats entry.

l2tpUdpStatsIfIndex.name: l2tpUdpStatsIfIndex
l2tpUdpStatsIfIndex.description: This value for this object is equal to the value of ifIndex of the Interfaces MIB for tunnel interfaces of type L2TP and which have a L2TP transport of UDP/IP.

l2tpUdpStatsPeerPort.name: l2tpUdpStatsPeerPort
l2tpUdpStatsPeerPort.description: This object reflects the peer's UDP port number used for this tunnel. When not known a value of zero should be returned.

l2tpUdpStatsLocalPort.name: l2tpUdpStatsLocalPort
l2tpUdpStatsLocalPort.description: This object reflects the local UDP port number that this tunnel is bound to.

l2tpTunnelAuthFailure.name: l2tpTunnelAuthFailure
l2tpTunnelAuthFailure.description: A l2tpTunnelAuthFailure trap signifies that an attempt to establish a tunnel to a remote peer has failed authentication.

l2tpMIBFullCompliance.name: l2tpMIBFullCompliance
l2tpMIBFullCompliance.description: When this MIB is implemented with support for read-create and read-write, then such an implementation can claim full compliance. Such an implementation can then be both monitored and configured with this MIB.

l2tpMIBReadOnlyCompliance.name: l2tpMIBReadOnlyCompliance
l2tpMIBReadOnlyCompliance.description: When this MIB is implemented without support for read-create and read-write (i.e. in read-only mode), then such an implementation can claim read-only compliance. Such an implementation can then be monitored but can not be configured with this MIB.

l2tpConfigGroup.name: l2tpConfigGroup
l2tpConfigGroup.description: A collection of objects providing configuration information of the L2TP protocol, tunnels and sessions.

l2tpStatsGroup.name: l2tpStatsGroup
l2tpStatsGroup.description: A collection of objects providing status and statistics of the L2TP protocol, tunnels and sessions.

l2tpIpUdpGroup.name: l2tpIpUdpGroup
l2tpIpUdpGroup.description: A collection of objects providing status and statistics of the L2TP UDP/IP transport layer.

l2tpDomainGroup.name: l2tpDomainGroup
l2tpDomainGroup.description: A collection of objects providing configuration, status and statistics of L2TP tunnel domains.

l2tpMappingGroup.name: l2tpMappingGroup
l2tpMappingGroup.description: A collection of objects providing index mapping.

l2tpSecurityGroup.name: l2tpSecurityGroup
l2tpSecurityGroup.description: A collection of objects providing L2TP security configuration.

l2tpTrapGroup.name: l2tpTrapGroup
l2tpTrapGroup.description: A collection of L2TP trap events as specified in NOTIFICATION-TYPE constructs.

l2tpHCPacketGroup.name: l2tpHCPacketGroup
l2tpHCPacketGroup.description: A collection of objects providing High Capacity 64-bit counter objects.
